":"1242–1304","1280–1334":"1280–1334","1282–Female":"1282–Deceased","1284–Female":"1284–Deceased","1286–Female":"1286–Deceased","1245–1304":"1245–1304","1304":"1304","about 1280":"about 1280","UM 1282":"about 1282","Aft 1304":"after 1304","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","UM 1284":"about 1284","1286":"1286","1242":"1242","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Germany","Augsburg, Stadt Augsburg, Bayern, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, Swabia, BY, Germany":"Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bach","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Fritz, Klaus, Horst, Johann, Alfons, Bernhard, Erna, Ernst.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a stream, Middle High German <i>bach</i> ‘stream’. This surname is also found in some other European countries, most notably in Denmark and France (Alsace and Lorraine), but also in e.g. the Netherlands, Czechia (see also 5 below), and Croatia.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Bach</i> ‘stream, creek’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bage","meanings":["English (Durham and Yorkshire): possibly from Middle English <i>bagge</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>bage</i> ‘badge, cognizance, emblem’, perhaps denoting someone who wore one as a sign of affiliation to a family or guild.","English: habitational name from The Bage in Dorstone, The Bage Farm in Madley, or Bage in Kington, all in Herefordshire. These are all names derived from Old English <i>bæce</i> ‘stream’; compare   Bach   3.","French: variant of <b>Bague</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bago</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bag</i> ‘to fight’."]},{"name":"Batch","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Bach   3."]},{"name":"Baughan","meanings":["Welsh: from the adjective <i>bychan</i> ‘little’, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> (see   Bach   4), originally in general used to distinguish father and son bearing the same name in genealogies. This word usually appears in Anglicized surnames in the lenited form   Vaughan  .","History: A Welsh family of this name was established from an early date in Great Rollright, Oxfordshire, England. The name was probably brought to North America from Oxfordshire rather than Wales."]},{"name":"Bartholomew","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Bertilmew</i>, <i>Bertelmy</i>, a borrowing of the Old French form of the Biblical personal name <i>Bartholomew</i> (from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i>; Hebrew ‘son of Talmai’, said to mean ‘having many furrows’, i.e. rich in land). This was an extremely popular personal name in Christian Europe, with many vernacular derivatives. It derived its popularity from the apostle Saint Bartholomew (Matthew 10:3), who was, among other things, the patron saint of tanners, vintners, and butlers.","As an Irish name, it has been used as an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Pharthaláin</b> (see   McFarlane  )."]},{"name":"Back","meanings":["English (Devon, Kent, Sussex, and Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bakke</i> (Old English <i>Bacca</i>). It is of uncertain origin, but may have been a byname in the same sense as 3.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘bat’, of uncertain application, perhaps a nickname for a person with poor eyesight, from the expression ‘blind as a bat’.","English: from Middle English <i>bakke</i> ‘back’ (Old English <i>bæc</i>), hence a nickname for someone with a hunched back or some other noticeable peculiarity of the back or spine, or a topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or ridge, or at the rear of a settlement."]},{"name":"Baugh","meanings":["Welsh: probably an Anglicized form of   Bach  , from Welsh <i>bach</i> ‘little’.","Americanized form of German   Bach  ."]},{"name":"Baechle","meanings":["South German (<b>Bächle</b>): Swabian-Alemannic variant of   Bach  , from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>bach</i> ‘stream’. Compare   Bachle   and   Beckley  ."]},{"name":"Bash","meanings":["English: variant of   Bach   3.","Jewish: acronymic surname from the first letters of Hebrew <i>ben</i> ‘son of’ and of a personal name such as <i>Shelomo</i> (see   Solomon  ), <i>Shemuel</i> (see   Samuel  ), <i>Shimon</i> (see   Simon  ) or <i>Shimshon</i> (see   Samson  ); see also   Brill  . In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the variant   Basch  .","Americanized form of German   Basch  ."]},{"name":"Bache","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Bach   1, 3.","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bach   6,   Bartholomew  ).","East German: occupational name for a butcher from Middle High German <i>bache</i> ‘ham, smoked slab of bacon’."]},{"name":"Bachofer","meanings":["German: topographic name for a farmer living by a stream (see   Bach   and   Hofer  )."]}]},{"name":"Heinrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>heim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  Henry ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Heinrich I. Bach was born in 1245, in Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Adelheid von Hohenlohe Brauneck Neuhaus. He died after 1304, in Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany."},"et":{"1245–Aft 1304":"1245–pärast 1304","1242–1304":"1242–1304","1280–1334":"1280–1334","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1245–1304":"1245–1304","1304":"1304","about 1280":"umbes 1280","UM 1282":"umbes 1282","Aft 1304":"pärast 1304","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","UM 1284":"umbes 1284","1286":"1286","1242":"1242","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Augsburg, Stadt Augsburg, Bayern, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Augsburg":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Augsburg, Swabia, BY, Germany":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1245–Aft 1304":"1245–1304 jälkeen","1242–1304":"1242–1304","1280–1334":"1280–1334","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1245–1304":"1245–1304","1304":"1304","about 1280":"noin 1280","UM 1282":"noin 1282","Aft 1304":"1304 jälkeen","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","UM 1284":"noin 1284","1286":"1286","1242":"1242","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Ulm, Baden-Württemberg, Saksa","Augsburg, Stadt Augsburg, Bayern, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa","Augsburg":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa","Augsburg, Swabia, BY, Germany":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa"},"fr":{"1245–Aft 1304":"1245–après 1304","1242–1304":"1242–1304","1280–1334":"1280–1334","1282–Female":"1282–Décédée","1284–Female":"1284–Décédée","1286–Female":"1286–Décédée","1245–1304":"1245–1304","1304":"1304","about 1280":"environ 1280","UM 1282":"environ 1282","Aft 1304":"après 1304","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","UM 1284":"environ 1284","1286":"1286","1242":"1242","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Ulm,